<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Spectral Reflectance Curve" class="currentChild" href="Spectral_Reflectance_Curve">Spectral Reflectance Curve</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
A curve that illustrates the reflectance of light from a surface, such as paper, wavelength-by-wavelength throughout the visible spectrum, as a means of determining the <a title="Color" href="Color">color</a> of that surface. Spectral reflectance curves are used to determine paper color, <a title="Brightness" href="Brightness">brightness</a>, and <a title="Whiteness" href="Whiteness">whiteness</a>, important optical properties that dramatically affect the quality of material printed on the paper surface. See <a title="Color" href="Color">Color</a>, <a title="Brightness" href="Brightness">Brightness</a>, and <a title="Whiteness" href="Whiteness">Whiteness</a>. 
</p>
